messages.text_en:
Scammers can obtain people’s personal data through neural networks. How can we protect ourselves?

All the information that users upload to chatbots with artificial intelligence can be leaked and made available to everyone. This includes photos, videos, documents, and personal emails. This is according to Lukas Safonov, an expert in information security and a business partner of the company Garda in terms of innovative development. A even more dangerous scenario is when users give access to their files to neural networks through browser notifications. In that case, the neural network can extract your personal data.

Such data leaks occur frequently due to poorly designed systems and hacker attacks on them. Additionally, certain services may not be well-protected, allowing anyone who wants to access all the conversations with the neural network to do so. If a user wants to delete a conversation, it will still remain on the neural network’s server, as the messages are stored in cloud storage or related bots.

What should not be shared with neural networks:
– Passport information, document numbers;
– Bank details, card numbers;
– Financial documents;
– Medical records containing personal data;
– Confidential documents;
– Personal emails without the consent of those involved in the conversation;
– Addresses and phone numbers of third parties;
– Photos and videos of intimate nature.

One of the most well-known cases of data leakage was when DeepSeek’s chatbot was hacked in 2025. The hackers gained access to all the data stored in the neural network. This put secret keys, unencrypted conversations, and logs at risk. Later, the Chinese developer fixed the vulnerability, limited public access to the service, and deleted the database from the internet. On January 20, 2026, another major data leak occurred with the popular AI app Chat & Ask AI. More than 300 million records were made available, including the entire history of conversations between 25 million people. Experts advise not to share personal information with neural networks or trust their responses.

